Parallel Data Load Group Id. This parameter is used for Parallel ASO Dataload.
Buffer Id. This parameter is used for Parallel ASO Dataload.
Buffer size. This parameter is used for Parallel ASO Dataload.

Option to clear data Essbase cube before loading data in it. Following are the valid values for it
- None: Clear database will not happen. - All: Clears all data blocks. - Upper Blocks: Clears all consolidated level blocks. - Non-Input Blocks: Clears blocks containing values derived from calculations.
Note: For ASO application, the Upper Blocks and Non-Input Blocks options will not be applicable.
The maximum number of allowed error

By default, this value is zero, which means that it will ignore any errors that occurs during the insert process into the target. If this is set to a value greater than zero, then, the load process will stop with an error once it reaches the specified number of errors.
Number of records to be sent to Essbase in a chunk.

(Optional) Name of the Rules file to be used for data load. If The rules file is present on Essbase Application then specify only the rules file name without separator otherwise specify rules filename with extension.
(Optional) Rule separator specified in the Rules file. Valid Values - Comma - Tab - Space - Custom character; for example, @, #, ^

(Optional) Name of the calculation script to be run after data load. If it is present on Essbase Application then specify only its name without separator otherwise specify rules filename with extension.
If Yes then executes the calculation script only and ignores all data from the source.
MAXL Script to be executed before loading data to the Essbase Cube.
Abort on pre load maxl error
This option would be applicable only if user specifies PRE_LOAD_MAXL script. Aborts the load process on encountering any error while executing pre-maxl script.
Execute MAXL script after data load
MAXL Script to be executed after loading data to the Essbase Cube.
Flag to indicate if logging should be performed during the load process. If set to Yes, logging would be done to the file specified by the LOG_FILE_NAME option.
The fully qualified name of the file into which logging is to be done.
If this option is set to "Yes", error records are logged to a file specified by the ERROR_LOG_FILENAME name option.
Specify the name of the file into which the error records should be logged.
Flag to log the header row
If this option is set to Yes, then the header row containing the column names is logged to the error records file.
The column delimiter for error file
The column delimiter to be used for the error records file.
The row delimiter for error file
The row delimiter to be used for the error records file.
The text delimiter for error file

The text delimiter to be used for the column data in the error records file. For e.g, if the text delimiter is set as ' " ' (double quote), then all the columns in the error records file will be delimited by double quotes.
